r 12 Music and Reuse Theoretical and Historical Considerations -- tChapter 13 Copyright, Music, and Morals Artistic Expression and the Public Sphere -- tAesth/ethic Epilogue Is Mozart’s Music Good? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the beginning of human civilization, music has been used as a device to control social behavior, where it has operated as much to promote solidarity within groups as hostility between competing groups. Music is an emotive manipulator that influences attitude, motivation and behavior at many levels and in many contexts. This volume is the first to address the social ramifications of music’s behaviorally manipulative effects, its morally questionable uses and control mechanisms, and its economic and artistic regulation through commercialization, thus highlighting not only music’s diverse uses at the social level but also the ever-fragile relationship between aesthetics and morality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aManipulative behavior. 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 0aSocial control. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBullerjahn, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCloonan, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDissanayake, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHargreaves, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorpe, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel